                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18350202-524-offence-1 t18350202-name-380"></join>John Underwood Smith</persName>; and 2 spoons, value 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., the goods of <persName id="t18350202-name-381" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-381" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-381" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-381" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18350202-524-offence-1 t18350202-name-381"></join>Richard Smith</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350202-name-382" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-382" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-382" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-382" type="given" value="MARIA"></interp>MARIA SMITH</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of Richard Smith, of Winchester-court, Monkwell-street. The prisoner came to my house, and slept one night—he gave my husband a written direction to go to the Custom-house, to get his luggage—he slept there that night, and had his breakfast and dinner the next day—at dinner-time my son came in, I said, "How long will your father be?" he said, "Two hours, for he is gone to the Custom-house"—the prisoner said, "I am very glad, for I shall have a change to put on"—I went down, and the prisoner said, "I will put this coat on, and go to see a young woman at the bottom of Silver-street, Falcon-square"—I said, "You will not be long?" he said, "No; because I expect your husband with my luggage"—he went off, and when my hus<lb></lb>band came home, he said, "Where is the young man?" I went to see after him, but he was not there—I then missed two silver spoons, which I had washed up with the tea-things that morning after breakfast—I have never seen them since.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350202-name-383" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-383" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-383" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350202-name-383" type="given" value="JOHN UNDERWOOD"></interp>JOHN UNDERWOOD SMITH</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the son of this witness. It was my great-coat the prisoner took—I afterwards met him in the street, and asked</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183502020063"></xptr>
               <p>him for it—he said, "What coat?" Le tried to get from me, but the policeman came up and took him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> I borrowed the coat; the spoons I never saw.</p>
